Computer-Vision GPU
For computer vision tasks, NVIDIA GPUs are generally preferred due to the robust CUDA ecosystem and specialized hardware like Tensor Cores, which accelerate deep learning workloads. The ideal GPU depends on your specific workload, budget, and scalability needs. 

Key Features to Consider
When choosing a GPU for computer vision, prioritize the following characteristics: 

VRAM (Video Memory) Amount: Crucial for handling large datasets and models (e.g., high-resolution images, large neural networks). More VRAM allows you to train larger models or use larger batch sizes.
CUDA Cores/Stream Processors: These are the individual processing units that perform parallel calculations. More cores mean faster parallel processing, which is fundamental to deep learning.
Tensor Cores: NVIDIA GPUs feature these specialized cores designed to accelerate matrix operations, which are at the heart of AI and deep learning computations, significantly speeding up training and inference.
Memory Bandwidth: Determines how quickly data can move in and out of the VRAM. High bandwidth is vital to prevent bottlenecks when processing large volumes of data.
Software Ecosystem: NVIDIA's CUDA platform provides extensive, highly-optimized libraries (cuDNN, TensorRT) and broad framework support (TensorFlow, PyTorch). AMD's ROCm is an open-source alternative but has less mature support across all frameworks.
Precision Support: Modern GPUs support various precision formats (FP32, FP16, FP8) which affect speed and memory usage. Ensure the GPU supports the precision level required by your models. 
